Radicals Blur Political Picture
Extremists seem to dominant American
politics today. They have not captured all
of the votes and offices as yet, but extras—
ist groups make so much noise with their
streaming that it is sometimes difficult to
hear anything else at all. The Bircllers export half the government as “communist
rules and sympathizers", While the far left
attributes all the World’s evil to Wall Street.
The right demands a withdrawal from
“dangerous internationalism" While the left
concerns the waste and insurance of a free
enterprise economy. The Americans for
Democratic Action and the Americans for
Constitutional Action trade results. The
National Review and the Fair Play for
Cuba Committee call each other ”minister
conspiracies."
It is completing to View these radical
groups as the creations of small minds.
They are discussed as fairly innocent
groups with simplified answers, catering to the unexpected All that is needed
is a little education, and then the radi<
cal cannon stand.
Ii we accept this promise, it should follow
that a student at an institution of higher
learning should be fairly interviews to the
attraction of their next answers and com
privacy theories. automatically he has more
knowledge than the average man, and has
more tools of analysis at his disposal. And
of course, he can always ask the opinion
of has faculty, who are even higher on the
scale of entertainment and consciousness.
He should be safe.
The unpleasant fact, however, is that
radical student groups of all kinds are
rapidly spreading across the country.
There have always been student groups
with extreme political views, but never before have they managed to grow so large,
so well organized. and so well finances.
The in left is represented by many
groups. The Students For a Democratic Society, which started in June 01 1962, is pro<
clarity an Eastern group, but is rapidly
spreading across the Country The Campus
Americans For Democratic Action is much
further to the left than its parent organize»
lion, the ADA. The Young Socialist Alliance has a number of growing chapters
across the country. New York City has ”.5
own local group, Advance, which has now
been infected under the Smith Act as a
CDmmlmlSerl‘int organization.
The right wing has only one major student organization, the Young Americans
for Freedom, but it is the largest and besttlnanced of all of the racial groups, The
YAF was set up In 1960 on the private estate of William Buckley, of National Review name. It now has more than 20,000
members across the country, as well as a
state of full-time officers. seniors and sen<
loss here will remember button Lewis III,
the YAF representative who Came to GX‘m‘
hell in 1962 to depend the House UnaAmerh
can ActiVllles Committee and the film “operation evolution".
Even more discussing is the extent to
which extremely groups have been able to
capture the national conventions ot/ the
Young Republicans and Young Democrats.
Last June's YR convention in San Francisco came out with an unbelievable platform, closely parallellng the views of the
John march Society. in September in San
Diego. the Young Democrats set ionh an
ultra~liberal platform which led several
prominent Democratic leaders, including
Governor Brown, to publicly immediate the
whole affair.
There is probably a higher percentage
of students in extremely organizations toe
day than from any other age or occupational group. The question of why is largely unanswered (and largely enabled). My
own hypothesis is the following:
3. Students DO have more political
information than the man on the street,
theoretical and rather supervision.
but this information is in most cases
There is lime real political insight on
today’s campus.
11. There is a certain excitement in
challenging accepted values and ways
of doing things.
1:. There is no real responsibility for
which most student groups are held accountable, ,such as running a government. These groups are not unlike processors in this regard.
d, There is real disillusionment‘with
the present system which allows discrimination, poverty, and violence on
the scale u-lat they exist. in this country.
These students want in change the system, and find the constitution of a new
system easier than modeling through
the complexities of the one that actually
exists.
 
