Hidden passengers to SGA Policies
Sympaihize with Administration Stand
To the editor:
For over year the problem
of what rules Grinnell students
really want‘has been with us.
We have regarded the Administration as our black advert
mary, our Enemy. But is it
really? We hay: sought
changes in some or the most
controversial rules — drinking,
opensrooms, and to a lesser extent, the car rule. The officials
of the college were supposed to
understand how deeply these
rules entrance upon our Individual Freedom, to expensive
with us, and to give us what
we want because we want it.
Yet how many or us have
sympathized, much less empathized, with the position or
the administration, who is
charged with maintaining
Grinnell’s public image and
continuing helpful parents,
alumni, and friends of the
college that it is not an
floral jungle, in order to
gain funds and support for
our progressive educational
program?
This year has seen many
changes, for example, the in
production of Grinnell Student
I. D. Cards, the evolution of the
10:30 night-check and the scoop—
arship restriction, and, above
all, a easily specialized drinking rule. "Other moderate,
changes are possiblei‘n the car
rule, in women's hours, and the
signrout procedure.
Instead, however, the SGA
has chosen to press such con»
troverSlal issues as the still
temporary open-rooms program, thus putting us all in a
very difficult position. First of
all, the suggested procedure'
seems to have latest opposition
in many quarters which has
been silent and which it seems
SGA officials have not made
great efforts to ascertain. A
references would be desirable.
recently, such legislation
puts the student body in an intensive position. shortly, the
p r o p o s e d open-rooms rule
places an unlair burden on
those who must efforts it.
We are living in this college
together ‘ students, faculty,
and administration, and as
such we students must at times
subordinate ourselves and our
desired to the unity of the
Whole. We have a responsible
its to understand as best we
can the limitations which a
rather closed community like a
college imposed, as well as enjoying the freedom and opportunities it offers.
Barbara burst
Ann Lousin
 
