Give Legal View
Of Civil Rights
By Phil Bernstein
In a coffee hour held Wednesday in Yollnker Lounge, Professor W, Bonfield of the driver—
site of Iowa Law School spoke
on the Kennedy Civil Rights
bill as Viewed by a contributions1 lawyer.
Bonfield stated that the bill‘s
passage was initiative not
only from a moral standpoint
but also in the light of the
sacred fred by discrimination
and of the financial and physical inconvenience which it
causes to all of us.
The Kennedy Bill would
make illegal any racial discuss—
station by hotels, stores, gas
stations, etc. which are in»
solved in interstate commerce,
It would also ban discrimination in movie theaters and
other places of entertainment
if either the nations or source
of entertainment had to cross
state boundaries.
In answer to those who would
still leave anti—discrimination
legislation up to the individual
states, Bonfield replied that
discrimination is, in
effect, a national problem and,
moreover. most state statutes
following it are rarely, if ever,
informed He pointed out that.
the Kennedy Bill draws its president from two sections of the
Constitution —- the Fourteenth
Amendment and the Commerce
Clause.
The more important of these
is the commerce clause, for it
is recognized that discrimination in the area of public accommodations has a direct and
negative bearing on interstate
commerce. The boycotts of
those fighting for equality have
the same skiﬂing effects as the
strikes of those who strike for
union recognition. That the
latter is now covered by the
National Labor Relations Act
(on the support of the come
mercy clause) gives president
to protecting the former under
a bill such as the Kennedy_
Civil Rights Bill.
Eonfield countries the states’
rights argument so often given
by Southerners by saying that
the {act that the month Amendment gives the stats only those
powers not previously generated to the Federal Government is irrelevant here because the Kennedy Bill draws
its support from generated
powers.
