SCARLET AND ILACK
Page Iiuven
 
 
By Len Calodney
In examining the possibility of putting face tasks on the IM
football sellers, we may now consider the problem from three
aspects: 1) how other schools have solved the problem, 2) what
julie coaches. medical personnel and insurance agents for the
college think about the suggestion, and a) how much it would
cost.
The smallest way to prevent intramural football injuries is to
not play the sport. This may have been the reason why Knox
never started football, but began their volleyball season in the
fall. The school may also have felt that in this way they word be
more likely to get all those of variety carrier out for football.
Princeton, on the other hand, has gone one step further and submitted lM players with shoulder pads as well as sellers. This
much equipment, besides being expensive, might make the game
a bit too rough for Grinnell's bloody
Football coach add powers is against the suggestion. He fears
that the addition of a face guard will give the IM player more
confidence for a head on charge, and thereby making the helmet
more of a weapon. He feels (that if the problem is not with
broken notes or blocked-out teeth, the face guard probably
won’t help too much, even though it would ward off a direct blow.
John deutsch (Athletic Director) suggests that we should concentrate on injuries over all rather than in one specific area, and
would rather see teaching and coaching used as a means to prevent injury, voting that football is the best part of the IM program, deutsch says it teaches many boys who never played a
Contact sport in high school what it means. deutsch added that he
would like to see the IM chairman come to the athletic staff for
help in running their teams, or for a clinic to be held for 1M
coaches.
As the one who is the ﬁrss to treat those fallen in battle, Mrs.
Irma Hall (Head Nurse) favors the move, She said she would
support anything to help reduce the number or injuries.
John C. Truesdale (Physical Education) has quoted the cost of
a single bar guard at $2. 25 Therefore the total cost for the 75
to 90 sellers would be about $150 200 Since the sellers now
used are variety cartoons, they have holes for face guard installation already skilled, so that additional work would not be
necessary.
Obviously the athletic department would not be able to budget
this much in one year for the purchase of a sufficient number of
face guards. However, the Insurance Company of North America, which handles Grinnell’s insurance business might be Willing
to help conduct an experiment here to see if face guards would
have some effect on injury rate,
Fred P. Ramsey (Ramsey Insurance Agency) mentioned that
the North American company had donated to Grinnell’s Ford
Foundation matching fund, but didn‘t know whether the company
would be Willing to sponsor this proposed experiment, Since this
company is paying $100 a year for head injuries at Grinneii, and
even though this figure means virtually nothing to the organize-
tion in comparison to its total volume of business, could we fri-~
forest the company in donation the equally miniature sum or $50,
enough for face guards on two strings of sellers?
(NEXT WEEK: How shall the experiment he conducted?
